        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Search-Based Planning Overview"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Search-based planning treats the planning problem as a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "state-space search"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": find a path from the initial state to a goal state by systematically applying actions. The key design choices are: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "search strategy"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (which nodes to expand next), "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "heuristic function"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (how to estimate remaining cost), and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "beam width"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (how many candidates to keep at each depth). These choices determine completeness, optimality, and computational cost."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Search strategy comparison: BFS explores all nodes level by level; A* prunes with heuristic; Beam Search keeps only top-k candidates at each level",
          "title": "BFS vs A* vs Beam Search trade-offs"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "In agentic AI, 'states' are plan prefixes and 'actions' are candidate next steps. The LLM provides both the successor generator and the heuristic evaluator, replacing the hand-coded components of classical search."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BFS and A*"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "BFS and A* are the two foundational algorithms. BFS explores level by level (shortest plan first); A* adds a heuristic to skip unpromising nodes. A* is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "optimal"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " when the heuristic "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "h(n)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "admissible"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " \u2014 it never overestimates the true remaining cost:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from collections import deque\nimport heapq\nfrom typing import Callable, Any\n\nState = Any   # any hashable node state\n\ndef bfs(\n    start: State,\n    is_goal: Callable[[State], bool],\n    get_successors: Callable[[State], list[tuple[str, State]]],\n) -> list[str] | None:\n    \"\"\"BFS \u2014 returns shortest-action-count path.\"\"\"\n    queue   = deque([(start, [])])   # (state, path_of_actions)\n    visited = {start}\n    while queue:\n        state, path = queue.popleft()\n        if is_goal(state):\n            return path\n        for action, next_state in get_successors(state):\n            if next_state not in visited:\n                visited.add(next_state)\n                queue.append((next_state, path + [action]))\n    return None\n\ndef astar(\n    start: State,\n    is_goal: Callable[[State], bool],\n    get_successors: Callable[[State], list[tuple[str, State, float]]],\n    heuristic: Callable[[State], float],\n) -> list[str] | None:\n    \"\"\"A* \u2014 returns lowest-cost path when heuristic is admissible.\n\n    get_successors returns (action, next_state, cost) triples.\n    \"\"\"\n    # heap: (f=g+h, g, state, path)\n    heap  = [(heuristic(start), 0.0, start, [])]\n    best  = {start: 0.0}   # best known g-cost per state\n    while heap:\n        f, g, state, path = heapq.heappop(heap)\n        if is_goal(state):\n            return path\n        for action, ns, cost in get_successors(state):\n            ng = g + cost\n            if ns not in best or ng < best[ns]:\n                best[ns] = ng\n                heapq.heappush(heap, (ng + heuristic(ns), ng, ns, path + [action]))\n    return None"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For LLM-based state spaces, the heuristic is typically an LLM score rather than a formal cost function. LLM heuristics are "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "not admissible"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " in general, so A* with an LLM heuristic loses the optimality guarantee \u2014 but in practice, it focuses the search much better than BFS."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Beam Search"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Beam search is BFS with a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "beam width"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " constraint: at each depth level, only the top-"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "k"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " states (by score) are kept. This trades completeness for memory efficiency. It is the dominant search strategy in language generation and LLM-based planning:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def beam_search(\n    start: State,\n    is_goal: Callable[[State], bool],\n    get_successors: Callable[[State], list[tuple[str, State]]],\n    score: Callable[[State], float],\n    beam_width: int = 4,\n    max_depth: int = 20,\n) -> list[str] | None:\n    \"\"\"Beam search \u2014 keeps the top-k states at each depth level.\n\n    score(state) returns a higher value for more promising states.\n    Not complete or optimal, but memory is O(beam_width) per level.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Beam: list of (state, path) pairs\n    beam = [(start, [])]\n\n    for depth in range(max_depth):\n        candidates: list[tuple[float, State, list[str]]] = []\n        for state, path in beam:\n            if is_goal(state):\n                return path\n            for action, ns in get_successors(state):\n                candidates.append((score(ns), ns, path + [action]))\n        if not candidates:\n            break\n        # Keep only top beam_width candidates\n        candidates.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        beam = [(ns, path) for _, ns, path in candidates[:beam_width]]\n\n    # No goal found in beam \u2014 return highest-scored path\n    if beam:\n        return beam[0][1]\n    return None"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Choosing beam width:"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " wider beams are more likely to find good plans but cost more. For LLM-backed scoring, beam_width=3\u20135 is a practical range \u2014 each successor requires an LLM call, so beam_width=10 makes each level 10x more expensive."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "LLM as Successor Generator and Scorer"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Replacing symbolic successor functions with LLM calls enables search over natural-language plan spaces where no formal domain model exists:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "SUCCESSOR_PROMPT = \"\"\"\nYou are generating the next possible steps from a given state in a planning task.\n\nGoal: {goal}\nCurrent state:\n{state}\n\nList the 3-5 most useful next actions from this state.\nReturn JSON: {{\"successors\": [\n  {{\"action\": \"<action_name>\", \"description\": \"<what it does>\"}}, ...\n]}}\n\"\"\"\n\nSCORE_PROMPT = \"\"\"\nRate how promising this plan state is for achieving the goal.\n\nGoal: {goal}\nActions taken so far: {actions}\nCurrent state: {state}\n\nReturn JSON: {{\"score\": 0.0-1.0, \"reason\": \"<one sentence>\"}}\n\"\"\"\n\ndef llm_successors(goal: str):\n    def get_successors(state: dict):\n        if state.get(\"depth\", 0) >= 6:\n            return []\n        response = client.messages.create(\n            model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n            max_tokens=512,\n            messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": SUCCESSOR_PROMPT.format(\n                goal=goal, state=state\n            )}],\n        )\n        data = json.loads(response.content[0].text)\n        return [\n            (s[\"action\"], {**state, \"last\": s[\"action\"], \"depth\": state.get(\"depth\", 0) + 1})\n            for s in data[\"successors\"]\n        ]\n    return get_successors\n\ndef llm_scorer(goal: str):\n    def score(state: dict) -> float:\n        response = client.messages.create(\n            model=\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\n            max_tokens=256,\n            messages=[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": SCORE_PROMPT.format(\n                goal=goal, actions=state.get(\"actions\", []), state=state\n            )}],\n        )\n        return float(json.loads(response.content[0].text)[\"score\"])\n    return score"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "depth"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " field in the state dictionary is the depth limit \u2014 it prevents infinite expansion. Without it, the LLM will keep generating successors even when the plan is already complete."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Greedy Best-First and Iterative Deepening"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Two additional strategies are useful in specific contexts: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "greedy best-first"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (expand only by heuristic, no path cost) is fast but not optimal; "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "iterative deepening DFS"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " achieves BFS completeness with DFS-level memory by repeating depth-limited searches:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def greedy_best_first(\n    start: State,\n    is_goal: Callable[[State], bool],\n    get_successors: Callable[[State], list[tuple[str, State]]],\n    heuristic: Callable[[State], float],\n) -> list[str] | None:\n    \"\"\"Greedy best-first search \u2014 always expands the state closest to goal.\n\n    Faster than A* but not optimal and can get stuck in local optima.\n    Uses only h(n), not g(n).\n    \"\"\"\n    heap    = [(heuristic(start), start, [])]\n    visited = {start}\n    while heap:\n        h, state, path = heapq.heappop(heap)\n        if is_goal(state):\n            return path\n        for action, ns in get_successors(state):\n            if ns not in visited:\n                visited.add(ns)\n                heapq.heappush(heap, (heuristic(ns), ns, path + [action]))\n    return None\n\ndef iterative_deepening(\n    start: State,\n    is_goal: Callable[[State], bool],\n    get_successors: Callable[[State], list[tuple[str, State]]],\n    max_depth: int = 10,\n) -> list[str] | None:\n    \"\"\"Iterative deepening DFS \u2014 BFS completeness with DFS memory.\n\n    Useful when the plan depth is unknown and memory is constrained.\n    \"\"\"\n    def dfs(state, path, limit):\n        if is_goal(state): return path\n        if len(path) >= limit: return None\n        for action, ns in get_successors(state):\n            if ns not in set(path):   # avoid cycles\n                result = dfs(ns, path + [action], limit)\n                if result is not None: return result\n        return None\n\n    for depth in range(1, max_depth + 1):\n        result = dfs(start, [], depth)\n        if result is not None:\n            return result\n    return None"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tree of Thought: Beam Search with LLM"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Tree of Thought"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (ToT) paradigm from research is a direct application of beam search: the LLM generates candidate next thoughts/actions, scores each one, and the beam keeps the top-k. This enables deliberate multi-step reasoning beyond single-pass generation:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Tree of Thought: beam search with LLM scoring, applied to plan generation\n\ndef tree_of_thought(\n    goal: str,\n    initial_state: dict,\n    beam_width: int = 3,\n    max_depth: int = 5,\n) -> list[str]:\n    \"\"\"Beam search planning with LLM-generated successors and LLM scoring.\n\n    This implements the Tree of Thought (ToT) paradigm:\n    - Successors are candidate next thoughts/actions (LLM-generated)\n    - Beam scoring is LLM-evaluated progress toward the goal\n    - Beam width controls the exploration-exploitation trade-off\n    \"\"\"\n    get_successors = llm_successors(goal)\n    scorer         = llm_scorer(goal)\n\n    def is_goal(state: dict) -> bool:\n        return state.get(\"depth\", 0) >= max_depth or state.get(\"goal_reached\", False)\n\n    plan = beam_search(\n        start=initial_state,\n        is_goal=is_goal,\n        get_successors=get_successors,\n        score=scorer,\n        beam_width=beam_width,\n        max_depth=max_depth,\n    )\n    return plan or []\n\n# Usage:\n# plan = tree_of_thought(\n#     goal=\"Write a Python function that reads CSV and outputs summary statistics\",\n#     initial_state={\"depth\": 0, \"actions\": [], \"context\": \"\"},\n#     beam_width=3,\n#     max_depth=5,\n# )"
          }
        ]
      },
